{"id":14881027,"mediaExerciseId":"77a56770-fff2-4bdc-8e89-895c35aa7455","exerciseName":"2","chapterName":"7","chapterTitle":"Interest Rates and Bond Valuation","groupId":null,"groupTitle":null,"isPremium":true,"sectionName":"7.2","sectionTitle":"More about Bond Features","pageNumber":211,"solutions":[{"id":5962459,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"This task asks **to determine the difference between debt and equity and explain the given terms.**\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":68,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/2734481b6004b511999772f92a9703d5/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":34,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/2734481b6004b511999772f92a9703d5/lateximg.png","width":497}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":"**a)**\n\nLet's explain the **main differences**.\n\n- When a company issues debt, there are no changes in the ownership. They have no right to vote.\n\n- The company that issues debt can deduct the interest from the payable tax amount. So, for the company is more cost expensive to issue debt.\n\n- When the company issues debt, the company has to repay it. If the company has no assets to pay the liabilities, the debtors have the legal right to ask for firm liquidation to help them receive the money back.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":331,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/806e3f040a3b3f78af5e949cc6436c61/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":166,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/806e3f040a3b3f78af5e949cc6436c61/lateximg.png","width":499}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"**b)**\n\n**Indenture** is the agreement between two entities on the market, the debtor and the lender. This agreement is in written form, and inside is written the terms that constrain this agreement, how to operate the sinking funds and what will happen if the debtor does not pay back the loan.\n","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":181,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/f73ef00d70f3c77591d33ab8a9055d61/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":91,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/f73ef00d70f3c77591d33ab8a9055d61/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"**A protective covenant** is one of the elements of indenture or other debt agreements. A protective covenant is a limitation that does not allow the debtor to take risky activities and put the company in a dangerous position. This limitation protects the lender and helps him receive the money back. ","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":143,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/125a3d7854e4546aca16642a1e8502ff/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":72,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/125a3d7854e4546aca16642a1e8502ff/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4},{"columns":[{"text":"There are two types of those covenants: what the debtor should do(positive) and what the debtor should not (negative).\n\n- An example of a positive protective covenant is that the firm must keep a minimum level of capital.\n\n- An example of a negative protective covenant is that while the company is repaying the debt, it can not merge with any other company.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":218,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/f5d9e6082ed116d6cdb8fd142fda8ff2/lateximg_large.png","width":997},"regular":{"height":110,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/f5d9e6082ed116d6cdb8fd142fda8ff2/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":5},{"columns":[{"text":"c)\n\nBefore the sinking fund, we have to explain a *bond trustee*. It is a financial institution that protects the debtholder and increases the trust that the debt issuer will repay the loan back. \n\nSo, the **sinking fund** is an account controlled by this financial institution for the bond repayment.","images":{"latex":{"large":{"height":218,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/3b3942da555265fb9646380307668fa4/lateximg_large.png","width":996},"regular":{"height":110,"srcUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/21/12/29/cf89e5ce6a143266590ac66a57b06f49/3b3942da555265fb9646380307668fa4/lateximg.png","width":498}},"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":false}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":6}],"rating":5,"solutionUuid":"00984cd4-c407-4131-bca4-9f151d2e007d","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":6}],"textbook":{"authors":"Bradford D. Jordan, Randolph W. Westerfield, Stephen A. Ross","imageUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/textbook_covers/tmpm0p82b7h","imageThumbnailUrl":"https://d2nchlq0f2u6vy.cloudfront.net/cache/d1/d3/d1d34d106dd29dd2e71be582412ef59d.jpg","id":34320,"isbn":"9781259918957","isPremium":true,"title":"Fundamentals of Corporate Finance","edition":"12th Edition","verifiedSolutionCount":1217,"shouldBeIndexableForSeo":true,"modified":1665448474394,"active":true,"publisher":"McGraw-Hill Education","mainTextbookIsbn":null,"subjects":{"level1":["Social Science"],"level2":["Economics"],"level3":["Finance"]}},"nextExercises":[{"id":14881028,"exerciseName":"3","page":212,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"f2060cad-0b33-4b9a-8791-9c72af22734e","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-7-exercises-3-f2060cad-0b33-4b9a-8791-9c72af22734e"}],"previousExercises":[{"id":14881026,"exerciseName":"1","page":205,"hasSolution":true,"mediaExerciseId":"1a8ddb75-15f6-48e6-aed4-33bc05cbb8b3","_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-7-exercises-1-1a8ddb75-15f6-48e6-aed4-33bc05cbb8b3"}],"_webUrl":"https://quizlet.com/explanations/textbook-solutions/fundamentals-of-corporate-finance-12th-edition-9781259918957/chapter-7-exercises-2-77a56770-fff2-4bdc-8e89-895c35aa7455"}